output.crosstab_text:
For level 8 graduates of Allied health, 5 years after graduation, the industry with the highest proportion of female graduates is Public administration and defence - compulsory social security, and the median earnings of females in this industry were £25,500. The industry with the highest proportion of male graduates was Education and the median earnings of males in this industry were £25,600.

The biggest difference in proportions is seen in Public administration and defence - compulsory social security where the proportion of female graduates is 19.1 percentage points higher than the proportion of male graduates. The biggest difference in median earnings is seen in Transportation and storage where the median earnings of female graduates were £25,500 higher than the median earnings of male graduates.The group with the highest earnings was male graduates in the Manufacturing industry (median earnings of £26,400).5.9% of female graduates are concentrated in the top 2 industries (either Education or Manufacturing), whereas for male graduates this is 0%.
output.crosstab_title: Industry of graduate employment for graduates of Allied health by sex, five years after graduation, male and female level 8 graduates from English HEIs, APs and FECs, 2018/19 tax year.
